## Defensive Coding

Always add fallbacks for potentially null/undefined values, especially in display components:

```typescript
// ✅ Safe - provides fallback for display
const displayName = user.name || user.email || 'Unknown';

// ✅ Safe - null coalescing for optional fields
const allocation = row.allocationPercent ?? 100;

// ❌ Unsafe - will crash if name is undefined
const initials = name.trim().slice(0, 2); // TypeError if name is undefined
```

## DataSource Development

### DataSource Hot-Reloading (Dev Mode)

In development mode, DataSource changes are automatically hot-reloaded without restarting the server. When you modify a DataSource definition file:

1. Save the file
2. Make any request (refresh the page)
3. The new DataSource definition is automatically loaded

**How it works:**
- `src/lib/server/init/init.ts` clears the require cache for DS files in dev mode
- Core's `addDataSources({ reload: true })` clears and reloads all DataSources
- No server restart needed for DS schema changes

**When to restart the server:**
- After modifying `init.ts` itself
- After changing core package code (rebuild core first)
- If hot-reload isn't picking up changes (rare)

### Adding Joined/Calculated Fields to DataSources

#### New Format (Recommended): Centralized Joins Array

Define joins in a centralized `joins` array for better clarity and maintainability:

```typescript
joins: [
  {
    alias: 'pm',
    tableName: 'uv_users',
    joinType: 'LEFT',
    on: 'pm.user_name = x.project_manager',
  },
],
attributes: [
  {
    ...DefaultAttribute,
    code: 'projectManager',
    name: 'Project Manager',
    type: 'Reference',
    column: 'project_manager',
    maxLength: 120,
    ref: { type: 'Text' },
    joinAlias: 'pm',  // Reference to join definition
  },
  {
    ...DefaultAttribute,
    code: 'projectManagerName',
    name: 'Project Manager Name',
    type: 'Text',
    column: 'pm.display_name',
    maxLength: 240,
    optional: true,
    joinAlias: 'pm',
    calculated: true,  // MUST be calculated (from joined table)
  },
],
```

**For nested joins:** Use explicit `dependsOn` field in the join definition:

```typescript
joins: [
  {
    alias: 'cust',
    tableName: 'customers',
    joinType: 'INNER',
    on: 'cust.customer_id = x.customer_id',
  },
  {
    alias: 'custType',
    tableName: 'customer_types',
    joinType: 'LEFT',
    on: 'custType.id = cust.type_id',
    dependsOn: 'cust',  // Explicit dependency
  },
],
```

#### Old Format (Backward Compatible)

The old attribute-based format is still supported for simple joins:

```typescript
{
  ...DefaultAttribute,
  code: 'projectManager',
  name: 'Project Manager',
  type: 'Reference',
  column: 'project_manager',
  maxLength: 120,
  ref: { type: 'Text' },
  refAlias: 'pm',
  refTableName: 'uv_users',
  refWhereClause: 'pm.user_name = x.project_manager',
  refEquiJoin: false,
},
```

**Note:** Old format only supports simple joins to main table. For nested joins, use the new `joins` array format.

**Important:** After adding DS fields, also update the TypeScript type in `src/lib/common/ds/types/`.

### Date Handling - Timezone Issues

When displaying dates from the database, use UTC methods to avoid timezone conversion issues:

```typescript
// ❌ Wrong - local timezone shifts the date
const formatDate = (date: string) => format(new Date(date), 'MMM yyyy');
// "2024-01-01T00:00:00Z" becomes "Dec 2023" in PST timezone

// ✅ Correct - use UTC methods
const formatDate = (date: string) => {
  const d = new Date(date);
  const months = ['Jan', 'Feb', 'Mar', 'Apr', 'May', 'Jun', 'Jul', 'Aug', 'Sep', 'Oct', 'Nov', 'Dec'];
  return `${months[d.getUTCMonth()]} ${d.getUTCFullYear()}`;
};
// "2024-01-01T00:00:00Z" correctly shows "Jan 2024"
```

**When to use UTC:**
- Displaying date-only values (no time component)
- Comparing dates across timezones
- Formatting dates for display where day matters

## Common Gotchas

### Click-Outside with Radix UI Portals

When building components with click-outside-to-close behavior that contain Radix UI components (ComboboxInput, SelectInput, Popover), dropdowns render in portals outside your container. Always check for Radix portal elements before canceling:

```typescript
function handleClickOutside(e: MouseEvent) {
  if (containerRef.current?.contains(e.target as Node)) return;
  // Check for Radix portals - dropdowns render outside the container
  const target = e.target as HTMLElement;
  if (target.closest('[data-radix-popper-content-wrapper]') || target.closest('[role="listbox"]')) {
    return;
  }
  handleCancel();
}
```

## Don'ts

- Don't use `console.log` - use `logger` on server, or allowed console methods (`console.info`, `console.warn`, `console.error`)
- Don't use `npm` or `yarn` - always use `pnpm`
- Don't create `.css` files - use Tailwind classes
- Don't use default exports for components
- Don't leave TODO comments or placeholders in code
- Don't use `any` unless absolutely necessary
- Don't use TypeScript enums - use const maps instead

